# Template Authoring

Files under `packages/cli/templates/pages/**` are scaffolded verbatim into
users' projects via the XDS CLI. Whatever ships here gets cloned into their
codebase, so keep templates clean and exemplary.

## No editorial / explanatory comments

Don't add notes, rationale, TODOs, or issue references that are meant for XDS
maintainers — users don't want that noise cloned into their files. Keep an
external issue open to track gaps instead of narrating them inline.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — ships maintainer commentary into user code
// NOTE: only custom styling here is image fill/cap/radius. XDS has no image
// primitive — no objectFit/maxWidth/radius props. Tracked in issue #2582.
const styles = stylex.create({
  // Fills the AspectRatio box. No objectFit prop on AspectRatio (#2582).
  heroImage: { width: '100%', height: '100%', objectFit: 'cover' },
});

// ✅ GOOD — clean, self-explanatory styles only
const styles = stylex.create({
  heroImage: { width: '100%', height: '100%', objectFit: 'cover' },
});
```

Comments that genuinely help a consumer understand the template are fine; the
rule targets maintainer-facing notes, not all comments.

## Images & assets (must be strippable)

Demo imagery is referenced from the `xds_oss` lookaside CDN — templates are NOT
shipped with committed image files. The docsite/sandbox previews load these
URLs directly; on scaffold (`xds template <name> <path>`), the CLI's
`stripTemplateAssetRefs()` (`packages/cli/src/api/template.mjs`) rewrites every
`lookaside.facebook.com/...` URL (and any legacy `/template-assets/<file>` path)
to a self-contained inline-SVG placeholder data-URI. This is what keeps a cloned
template from shipping broken images / a Meta-only network dependency into a
user's project — builders then drop in their own art.

For this to work, reference the asset as a **plain string literal** so the
stripper can see it:

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — dynamic path; stripper can't see it, ships a Meta-only ref
const IMG_DIR = `${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_BASE_PATH ?? ''}/assets`;
const src = `${IMG_DIR}/cover.png`;

// ✅ GOOD — plain lookaside literal, gets replaced by the placeholder on scaffold
const src = 'https://lookaside.facebook.com/assets/xds_oss/cover.png';
```

Genuinely external, non-Meta image URLs (e.g. third-party brand logos like
`paypalobjects.com` or `raw.githubusercontent.com`) are intentionally left
untouched by the stripper, so a scaffolded page keeps working logos rather than
placeholdering them.
